# Project Rules

Before creating or modifying UI components, ALWAYS reference design-system.md.

Use ONLY CSS variables defined in globals.css. No hardcoded values.

## Rule Priority (Mandatory)

These rules are NOT suggestions. They are hard requirements.

- MUST follow this file before any implementation choices
- MUST treat violations as bugs, not style preferences
- MUST prefer consistency with existing tokens/patterns over convenience
- MUST stop and fix rule violations before presenting final output
- MUST ask for explicit user approval before making an exception

If there is any conflict, follow this order:

1. This `.cursorrules` file
2. `design-system.md`
3. Existing local file patterns
4. Personal/default assistant preferences

## Enforcement Checklist (Run Before Final Response)

- No hardcoded color/spacing/size values when token exists
- Tailwind spacing/sizing uses CSS vars (e.g. `px-[var(--spacing-sm)]`)
- No manual `dark:` variants for theme colors
- No hardcoded text in components (content comes from `src/data/`)
- If a violation was introduced, fix it before finishing

When using Tailwind:

- Use arbitrary values to reference CSS vars: `bg-[var(--color-primary)]`
- Or use custom component classes defined in globals.css
- NEVER use arbitrary Tailwind values (no p-7, no text-gray-650)
- NEVER hardcode colors (no #3b82f6, no rgb values)
- NEVER use numeric Tailwind spacing/sizing utilities in UI code when a spacing token applies (e.g. `p-4`, `px-6`, `gap-3`, `h-10`, `w-10`)
- Prefer tokenized values: `p-[var(--spacing-sm)]`, `gap-[var(--spacing-xs)]`, `h-[var(--spacing-xl)]`

Dark mode is handled automatically via CSS variables in globals.css - do not add manual dark: variants.

When creating reusable component patterns, add them to globals.css using @apply in the @layer components section.

## Layout & Responsiveness

- ALL components must be fully mobile responsive

## CSS Abstraction Guidelines

**Gradients:**

- ALL gradients must be defined in `src/styles/gradients.css`
- If gradients.css doesn't exist, create it
- Import gradients.css in root layout.tsx after globals.css
- Define gradients as CSS custom properties or utility classes
- Reference in components via CSS variables or class names
- NEVER define gradients inline in JSX or component styles

**CSS vs Tailwind Separation:**

- NEVER mix complex pure CSS with Tailwind utility classes in the same element
- If a component needs custom CSS beyond simple Tailwind utilities, extract it to a dedicated CSS class in globals.css or component-scoped CSS
- This prevents hot reload issues and keeps styling predictable
- Use Tailwind for layout/spacing/simple styles, CSS classes for complex custom styling

**Add to globals.css ONLY if:**
...

**Add to globals.css ONLY if:**

- The pattern could naturally be used across 3+ DIFFERENT types of components (e.g., `.card` applies to any card-like UI element)
- It's a primitive UI element (button, input, badge, etc.)
- It defines a semantic pattern that should be consistent everywhere (containers, grids)

**Keep in component JSX if:**

- The pattern is specific to one component's unique structure (even if that component is reused multiple times)
- The class name includes or implies a specific component (`.split-section`, `.hero-layout`)
- It describes "how this particular component is laid out" rather than "a reusable primitive"

**Examples:**

✅ Add to globals.css:

```css
.card { ... }          /* Used by many card-type components */
.button-primary { ... } /* Used across all primary buttons */
.container { ... }      /* Standard content width container */
```

❌ Keep in component:

```tsx
/* This is SplitSection's layout, not a global pattern */
```

**Rule of thumb: If you can't give it a generic name (without the component name in it), it shouldn't be in globals.css**

Examples:

- `.card` → Generic ✅
- `.split-section` → Component-specific ❌
- `.button-primary` → Generic ✅
- `.hero-layout` → Component-specific ❌

## Global Components

- Navbar/Header and Footer components belong ONLY in root layout.tsx
- Page routes contain page-specific content

## Content Management

ALL text content must be separated from components and stored in src/data/.

**File Structure:**

- Global content (nav, footer): `src/data/navigation.ts`, `src/data/footer.ts`
- Page-specific content: `src/data/pages/[pagename].ts`
- Reusable component content: `src/data/sections/[componentname].ts`

**Component Data Patterns:**

There are three patterns for how components consume data:

1. **Page-specific components** - Import data directly from `/data/pages/`

```tsx
// Data file: /data/pages/home.ts
export const homeContent = {
  hero: { title: "...", subtitle: "..." },
};
// NO type export

// Component file
import { homeContent } from "@/data/pages/home";

export function Hero() {
  return <h1>{homeContent.hero.title}</h1>;
}
```

- No type export needed
- Component imports and uses data directly

2. **Dynamic reusable components** - Accept different content via props

```tsx
   // Data file: /data/sections/split-image-text.ts
   export const splitImageTextContent = { ... };
   export type SplitImageTextContent = typeof splitImageTextContent;

   // Component file
   import type { SplitImageTextContent } from '@/data/sections/split-image-text';

   interface SplitImageTextProps {
     content: SplitImageTextContent;
   }

   export function SplitImageText({ content }: SplitImageTextProps) {
     return <h1>{content.heading}</h1>;
   }

   // Usage - can pass different content each time
   <SplitImageText content={aboutContent.section1} />
   <SplitImageText content={aboutContent.section2} />
```

- MUST export type using `typeof`
- Component accepts `content` prop
- Can render different data per usage

3. **Encapsulated reusable components** - Import fixed data internally

```tsx
   // Data file: /data/sections/contact.ts
   export const contactSectionContent = { ... };
   // Type export optional (only if needed for tests/stories)

   // Component file
   import { contactSectionContent } from '@/data/sections/contact';

   export function ContactSection() {
     return <h1>{contactSectionContent.title}</h1>;
   }

   // Usage - no props, always same content
   <ContactSection />
```

- Type export optional
- Component imports data directly (same as page-specific)
- Always renders same content

**General Content Rules:**

- NEVER hardcode text strings in components
- Use clear, semantic key names (hero, features, testimonials) - avoid generic names (section1, data)
- Use camelCase for all keys
- If no content provided, use clear placeholder text in data objects

## TypeScript & Data Types

**Why use `typeof` for dynamic reusable components:**

- Data object defines structure once
- Type derives automatically (stays in sync)
- Prevents duplicate type definitions
- Change data → type updates automatically

**Type Export Rules:**

- Dynamic reusable (`/data/sections/`) → MUST export type: `export type [Name]Content = typeof [name]Content;`
- Page-specific (`/data/pages/`) → NEVER export types
- Encapsulated reusable (`/data/sections/`) → Optional type export

**Forbidden Patterns:**

- NEVER create local interfaces that duplicate data structure
- NEVER use `typeof` inline in props: `content: typeof servicesSectionContent`
- NEVER create intermediate type aliases that just rename imported types
- NEVER export types from page-specific data files (`/data/pages/`)
- NEVER spread data objects as props: `<Component {...data} />`
- ALWAYS pass data as explicit named prop: `<Component content={data} />`
- NEVER mix UI configuration flags into data objects - keep content and UI config separate

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG - Creating duplicate type structure
interface ServiceItem {
  icon: string;
  title: string;
}
interface ServicesSectionProps {
  items: ServiceItem[];
}

// ✅ CORRECT - Single type derived from data
import type { ServicesSectionContent } from "@/data/sections/services";

interface ServicesSectionProps {
  content: ServicesSectionContent;
}
```

## Typography

- Primary Font: `var(--font-primary)` - Use for all text
- Secondary Font: `var(--font-secondary)` - Only use when explicitly instructed (e.g., code blocks)
- Body text uses primary font by default
- Fonts are defined in layout.tsx and can be changed there without modifying CSS

## Background Elevation

- `var(--background)` - Page/section backgrounds
- `var(--background-elevated)` - Cards, containers, sections
- `var(--background-elevated-high)` - ONLY for floating overlays (modals, dropdowns, tooltips) - use sparingly

## Interaction & Animation

- Simple UI toggles may use native HTML semantics (e.g. <details>) where appropriate
- If an interaction requires custom enter/exit animations, height/layout animations, coordinated open/close behavior, or future extensibility beyond basic toggling, THEN prefer React-managed state using hooks (useState, useEffect)
- In such cases:
  - Mark components as "use client"
  - Use React state to control interaction
  - For animations, follow this priority:
    1. Tailwind transition utilities (transition-colors, transition-opacity, etc.) for simple state changes
    2. Framer Motion library for all other animations (enter/exit, layout, gestures, complex sequences)
    3. Raw CSS only as last resort or when Motion has API limitations

Do not refactor, restructure, or modify any code that I have personally added or changed unless I explicitly instruct you to do so.
